The paper deals with clustering problems, which are typically studied in the subfield of data structures (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG). The notion of perturbation resilience is related to information theory (cs.IT) and computational complexity (cs.CC), as it involves analyzing the effect of small changes in the input on the output of an algorithm. Finally, the use of center-based objectives suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI), where clustering is often used as a preprocessing step for other tasks.
